    <title>Networking</title>
    <briefdescription>
    </briefdescription>
    <detaileddescription>
<para>Retro Rocket includes basic networking support so you can connect to the internet and use network-enabled programs.</para>
<para><hruler/>
</para>
<sect1 id="user-networking_1network-drivers_1s1"><sect2 id="user-networking_1network-drivers_1s2"><sect3 id="user-networking_1network-drivers">
<title>Network Drivers</title><para><itemizedlist>
<listitem><para>The network driver is loaded in the <bold>boot script</bold> <computeroutput>/programs/init</computeroutput>.</para>
</listitem><listitem><para>By default, Retro Rocket loads the <bold>e1000</bold> driver, which also supports the Intel 82541PI chipset.</para>
</listitem><listitem><para>On an installed system, you can freely edit <computeroutput>/programs/init</computeroutput> (using the <computeroutput>edit</computeroutput> command) to change which driver is loaded.</para>
</listitem></itemizedlist>
</para>
<para>For most users the default works automatically.</para>
<para><hruler/>
</para>
</sect3></sect2></sect1>
<sect1 id="user-networking_1network-configuration_1s1"><sect2 id="user-networking_1network-configuration_1s2"><sect3 id="user-networking_1network-configuration">
<title>Network Configuration</title><para>Once the network driver has been initialised, the system reads its configuration from:</para>
<para><programlisting><codeline><highlight class="normal">/system/config/network.conf</highlight></codeline>
</programlisting></para>
<para>This file controls how your machine identifies itself and how it connects.</para>
<sect4 id="user-networking_1example-default-configuration">
